An enum value in Java is an object. An object is an instance of a type. In this case, the type is the enum, (&quot;Locale&quot;,) so the enum values are instances of that type, in other words, each enum value is of type &quot;Locale&quot;. Java guarantees that there will only be a fixed set of instances, one instance for each value declared in the enum. 

When you declare a constructor and fields in an `enum`, these become part of each instance. So, each one of the locales you have declared will have an extra member of type `String` which you call `locale`.

Knowing that, and also knowing that to get all instances, we can use `Locale.values()`, your answer is:

    for( var instance : Locale.values() )
        System.out.println( instance.locale );

The [Answer by Mike Nakis][1] is correct. I can clarify a bit more.

Let&#39;s change the names in the original code, for clarity. 

As [commented by andrewJames][2], Java bundles a commonly used class named `Locale`. So let&#39;s change your enum name to be more specific, something like `LocaleCode`. 

And change the field name to be more specific: `code`. 

The `code` field holding the `String` object should be private, to prevent inadvertent re-assignment to another object. Add a getter method to access that string.

For fun, we can add a convenience method to return a [`java.util.Locale`][3] object matching our stored code string. By the way, the order of language and culture in your string codes seems to be the reverse of conventional/standard order (but I am no expert). 


```java
package work.basil.example;

import java.util.Locale;

public enum LocaleCode
{
    PL( &quot;PL-pl&quot; ),
    DE( &quot;DE-de&quot; ),
    EN( &quot;EN-en&quot; );

    // Member field
    private final String code;

    // Constructor
    private LocaleCode ( String code )
    {
        this.code = code;
    }

    // Getter method for private field.
    public String getCode ( )
    {
        return code;
    }

    // Convenience method for obtaining a `java.util.Locale` object for this code.
    public Locale getLocale ( )
    {
        
    }
}
```

